- Hi.

01:09:01.520 --> 01:09:03.450
I'm Kathryn Sikkink,
and I'm a faculty member

01:09:03.450 --> 01:09:06.779
at the Kennedy School and
a Radcliffe professor.

01:09:06.779 --> 01:09:08.520
In terms of expanding
the electorate,

01:09:08.520 --> 01:09:11.160
we haven't heard much about
the youth vote and the college

01:09:11.160 --> 01:09:11.859
vote.

01:09:11.859 --> 01:09:13.330
And we're here on campus.

01:09:13.330 --> 01:09:17.000
And so we know that youth
voters and college voters

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:20.399
vote at some of the lowest
levels of any people

01:09:20.399 --> 01:09:21.600
in the electorate.

01:09:21.600 --> 01:09:24.600
I've also heard-- but I
have not had confirmed--

01:09:24.600 --> 01:09:27.990
that there was about a 10%
increase in this midterm as

01:09:27.990 --> 01:09:29.295
compared to the last midterm.

01:09:29.295 --> 01:09:30.920
So could you just
tell us a little more

01:09:30.920 --> 01:09:33.630
what we know about the
youth vote, and the college

01:09:33.630 --> 01:09:37.260
vote in the midterms?

01:09:37.260 --> 01:09:37.979
- Sure.

01:09:37.979 --> 01:09:39.957
To your question
about the numbers,

01:09:39.957 --> 01:09:41.790
there are unconfirmed
numbers at this point.

01:09:41.790 --> 01:09:43.950
I know CIRCLE over
at Tufts University

01:09:43.950 --> 01:09:46.260
does really good analysis
on the youth voter turnout,

01:09:46.260 --> 01:09:50.414
and did find the estimates
to be about 10% higher.

01:09:50.414 --> 01:09:52.080
I think we'll get a
better sense of that

01:09:52.080 --> 01:09:55.750
once the census numbers come
out, which are self-reported.

01:09:55.750 --> 01:09:58.500
But overall, I feel like most
people will say confidently,

01:09:58.500 --> 01:10:00.570
youth voter turnout was up.

01:10:00.570 --> 01:10:04.050
I think the conundrum people
run into a little bit is--

01:10:04.050 --> 01:10:05.700
Florida's a really
good case study.

01:10:05.700 --> 01:10:07.800
I talked to both
Democrats and Republicans

01:10:07.800 --> 01:10:12.040
who'll both admit and say
youth voter turnout was up.

01:10:12.040 --> 01:10:14.560
But the problem is everybody's
voter turnout was up.

01:10:14.560 --> 01:10:16.920
I mean, the problem for
Democrats, in that situation,

01:10:16.920 --> 01:10:19.950
was that, as a result,
there was expected

01:10:19.950 --> 01:10:22.920
to be a huge uptick
because of the results

01:10:22.920 --> 01:10:25.230
of the school shooting
at Parkland and whatnot,

01:10:25.230 --> 01:10:27.150
and they did not see
that manifest itself

01:10:27.150 --> 01:10:29.864
fully in the general election.

01:10:29.864 --> 01:10:32.280
And Florida, I think, is a
really good case study of that,

01:10:32.280 --> 01:10:35.730
because you have polar
opposite extremes in terms

01:10:35.730 --> 01:10:39.562
of the age electorate there.

01:10:39.562 --> 01:10:42.060
- Thank you.

01:10:42.060 --> 01:10:42.560
- Hi.

01:10:42.560 --> 01:10:43.960
I'm Julio Ricardo Varela.

01:10:43.960 --> 01:10:50.230
I'm a journalist and a proud
alumnus of the college of 1990.

01:10:50.230 --> 01:10:52.690
Asma, you mentioned Florida.

01:10:52.690 --> 01:10:56.110
And I'm glad, because I
wanted to know, particularly

01:10:56.110 --> 01:10:59.320
from Robert and Aimee--
because the notion

01:10:59.320 --> 01:11:03.880
of the multiracial,
multi-ethnic coalition, no one

01:11:03.880 --> 01:11:06.830
used Florida as an example.

01:11:06.830 --> 01:11:10.750
And actually, is
Florida the national--

01:11:10.750 --> 01:11:13.730
are we going to become
Florida as a nation?

01:11:13.730 --> 01:11:16.860
And I say that because--

01:11:16.860 --> 01:11:21.960
and I point to your side,
Robert, about the Latina vote.

01:11:21.960 --> 01:11:26.950
Black women, totally Democratic.

01:11:26.950 --> 01:11:30.380
Latina women, 27%
voted for Donald Trump,

01:11:30.380 --> 01:11:31.510
or voted Republican.

01:11:31.510 --> 01:11:33.760
And also, if you look
at the numbers in 2016--

01:11:33.760 --> 01:11:37.720
and Florida's the perfect case,
because when you have DeSantis

01:11:37.720 --> 01:11:41.180
telling people that Gillum's
going to turn Florida

01:11:41.180 --> 01:11:44.029
into Venezuela, then you have
one extreme to the other,

01:11:44.029 --> 01:11:45.820
and it kind of speaks
to Sarah's point too.

01:11:45.820 --> 01:11:49.240
So I'd love to hear what you
guys think about Florida,

01:11:49.240 --> 01:11:52.990
because it kind of goes against
the winning-is-losing type.

01:11:52.990 --> 01:11:53.920
Or what do you think?

01:11:53.920 --> 01:11:56.009
Because it's not so cut and dry.

01:11:56.009 --> 01:11:56.800
So I'm curious to--

01:11:56.800 --> 01:11:58.240
- Can I just give
you a quick summary?

01:11:58.240 --> 01:11:59.740
Just because I
actually specifically

01:11:59.740 --> 01:12:02.290
looked at the Florida Latino
population just a couple

01:12:02.290 --> 01:12:05.410
of weeks ago, actually, to
answer that specific question.

01:12:05.410 --> 01:12:07.810
And I think that, in Florida,
there were two really

01:12:07.810 --> 01:12:08.800
interesting dynamics.

01:12:08.800 --> 01:12:11.980
One is Rick Scott, who was
running for the Senate seat,

01:12:11.980 --> 01:12:14.560
explicitly courted the
Hispanic vote in a way

01:12:14.560 --> 01:12:16.697
that I would argue
other Republicans ought

01:12:16.697 --> 01:12:17.530
to pay attention to.

01:12:17.530 --> 01:12:18.000
It was highly successful.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:19.900
- And the Puerto Rican
vote in central Florida.

01:12:19.900 --> 01:12:20.400
- Exactly.

01:12:20.400 --> 01:12:22.090
He was doing Spanish
language ads.

01:12:22.090 --> 01:12:25.130
He taught himself
Spanish through an aide.

01:12:25.130 --> 01:12:26.140
So that was one factor.

01:12:26.140 --> 01:12:28.270
The other people
pointed me towards

01:12:28.270 --> 01:12:31.720
is that DeSantis, who is now
going to be the governor,

01:12:31.720 --> 01:12:34.210
his running mate
was a very popular

01:12:34.210 --> 01:12:37.390
Cuban-American legislator,
and she heavily

01:12:37.390 --> 01:12:40.120
focused on upping
that population.

01:12:40.120 --> 01:12:42.220
And so as a result,
I think many people

01:12:42.220 --> 01:12:45.550
thought Barack Obama did
pretty well with parts

01:12:45.550 --> 01:12:48.479
of the Cuban population in
Florida that seemed to revert.

01:12:48.479 --> 01:12:50.770
I don't know if revert's the
right-- because who knows?

01:12:50.770 --> 01:12:52.790
Maybe these were
different Cuban voters.

01:12:52.790 --> 01:12:54.010
It was an older electorate.

01:12:54.010 --> 01:12:56.020
But I think that that's
a really good question,

01:12:56.020 --> 01:12:57.821
because it showed,
to me, inroads

01:12:57.821 --> 01:13:00.070
that Republicans have been
able to make in that state.

01:13:00.070 --> 01:13:00.520
But please--

01:13:00.520 --> 01:13:01.890
- I'm curious what you
guys have about this.

01:13:01.890 --> 01:13:02.390
Thank you.

01:13:02.390 --> 01:13:04.120
- Yeah.

01:13:04.120 --> 01:13:06.630
I will say-- when you say,
is the country become--

01:13:06.630 --> 01:13:09.230
there's no monolith
among Latinos.

01:13:09.230 --> 01:13:11.620
I don't have to tell you that.

01:13:11.620 --> 01:13:12.890
- [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:12.890 --> 01:13:14.390
[CHUCKLING]

01:13:14.390 --> 01:13:17.140
- What the strategists
