01:19:51.349 --> 01:19:53.620
I like that comment.

01:19:53.620 --> 01:19:57.040
- I really care about
what happens in 2020.

01:19:57.040 --> 01:20:00.760
And I want the Democrats
to just prevail.

01:20:00.760 --> 01:20:04.300
And so what's been
really insightful to me--

01:20:04.300 --> 01:20:07.090
and I thank you for
presenting it-- is identifying

01:20:07.090 --> 01:20:09.820
constituencies where
it's strategically

01:20:09.820 --> 01:20:14.140
really wise for Democratic
candidates to invest.

01:20:14.140 --> 01:20:16.520
Expanding the electorate.

01:20:16.520 --> 01:20:23.900
I was heartened by the vote
in Florida that expanded

01:20:23.900 --> 01:20:26.045
the vote to former-- to felons.

01:20:28.705 --> 01:20:30.730
And obviously, there's
some constituencies

01:20:30.730 --> 01:20:32.820
where there's no point.

01:20:32.820 --> 01:20:36.410
It would be a fool's errand
to try to change their minds.

01:20:36.410 --> 01:20:37.840
But I think there's a large--

01:20:37.840 --> 01:20:40.372
I'm particularly interested
in the work that you're doing,

01:20:40.372 --> 01:20:41.830
Dr. Cramer, because
I think there's

01:20:41.830 --> 01:20:47.830
a large part of our society
who have been left behind

01:20:47.830 --> 01:20:52.180
by the evolutionary
trajectory of our economy.

01:20:52.180 --> 01:20:56.140
And along with it is identity
things, as you mentioned.

01:20:56.140 --> 01:21:01.690
And it's a loss of
sense of your status

01:21:01.690 --> 01:21:05.380
in our society,
your personal honor,

01:21:05.380 --> 01:21:09.430
apart from or in addition
to your economic struggles

01:21:09.430 --> 01:21:12.520
that go along with
those economic trends.

01:21:12.520 --> 01:21:18.700
So I think the listening
project that you're initiating

01:21:18.700 --> 01:21:24.610
is maybe the key to
helping Democrats

01:21:24.610 --> 01:21:33.730
know how to identify and address
the issues that resulted in--

01:21:36.025 --> 01:21:37.400
- Can I just ask
just real quick?

01:21:37.400 --> 01:21:38.300
Sorry, do you have a question?

01:21:38.300 --> 01:21:39.640
Just because you have
like 30 seconds--

01:21:39.640 --> 01:21:39.812
- Yeah.

01:21:39.812 --> 01:21:40.312
OK.

01:21:40.312 --> 01:21:42.119
Well, Staten is a
really great case,

01:21:42.119 --> 01:21:43.410
because it used to be Democrat.

01:21:43.410 --> 01:21:44.800
It used to be
really progressive,

01:21:44.800 --> 01:21:47.690
and now it has
gone the other way.

01:21:47.690 --> 01:21:50.860
So what do you
think you can learn

01:21:50.860 --> 01:21:54.640
that would be good counsel
for Democrats addressing

01:21:54.640 --> 01:21:56.352
that population?

01:21:56.352 --> 01:21:59.490
- Well, we're hoping
that the project helps

01:21:59.490 --> 01:22:02.850
politicians of all
stripes better understand

01:22:02.850 --> 01:22:04.350
the people that they represent.

01:22:04.350 --> 01:22:08.320
Because one thing-- probably
goes without saying,

01:22:08.320 --> 01:22:11.634
but politicians these days
spend so much time raising money

01:22:11.634 --> 01:22:13.800
that they actually don't
have the luxury of inviting

01:22:13.800 --> 01:22:17.680
themselves into conversations
in gas stations, like I do,

01:22:17.680 --> 01:22:19.110
which is a real shame.

01:22:19.110 --> 01:22:23.430
So we're hoping that it
lends insights to politicians

01:22:23.430 --> 01:22:27.121
of a variety of parties.

01:22:27.121 --> 01:22:27.620
- Great.

01:22:27.620 --> 01:22:28.375
Thank you.

01:22:28.375 --> 01:22:29.750
I know we're
running out of time,

01:22:29.750 --> 01:22:31.833
but why don't we take just
this one last question?

01:22:31.833 --> 01:22:32.690
I apologize.

01:22:32.690 --> 01:22:34.040
- I'm Lewis [INAUDIBLE].

01:22:34.040 --> 01:22:36.560
My question goes to economics.

01:22:36.560 --> 01:22:38.840
The last two
election cycles have

01:22:38.840 --> 01:22:42.950
occurred during a period of
expansion in the economy.

01:22:42.950 --> 01:22:45.230
Not all people have
participated in that.

01:22:45.230 --> 01:22:46.950
That led to resentment.

01:22:46.950 --> 01:22:48.770
It's increasingly
likely we're going

01:22:48.770 --> 01:22:52.640
to see a major economic
disruption in the next two

01:22:52.640 --> 01:22:53.880
years.

01:22:53.880 --> 01:22:55.760
The closing of
General Motors plants

01:22:55.760 --> 01:22:59.780
are just the first two steps in
a radical change in our economy

01:22:59.780 --> 01:23:01.940
that will occur.

01:23:01.940 --> 01:23:07.160
What impact do you think this
probable economic downturn

01:23:07.160 --> 01:23:09.950
is going to have on
the next election,

01:23:09.950 --> 01:23:13.280
since the last two
elections were fought,

01:23:13.280 --> 01:23:16.590
whatever people said in
an expanding economy,

01:23:16.590 --> 01:23:20.171
and that's highly
unlikely for 2020?

01:23:20.171 --> 01:23:21.630
- It's hard to know.

01:23:21.630 --> 01:23:24.040
People are talking about
a recession in two years,

01:23:24.040 --> 01:23:26.820
but when will people
start feeling that?

01:23:26.820 --> 01:23:29.350
So I think that it's important--

01:23:29.350 --> 01:23:29.850
- Yeah.

01:23:29.850 --> 01:23:30.660
And not to cut you off--

01:23:30.660 --> 01:23:31.368
- No, no, no, go.

01:23:31.368 --> 01:23:36.360
- I think there are a lot of
people who work full-time who

01:23:36.360 --> 01:23:38.400
are still poor.

01:23:38.400 --> 01:23:45.930
And that sense of
not being heard,

01:23:45.930 --> 01:23:48.120
that's why I think
there's such momentum

01:23:48.120 --> 01:23:50.310
around a $15 minimum wage.

01:23:50.310 --> 01:23:54.300
Even a lot of Democrats
have rejected that notion

01:23:54.300 --> 01:23:55.890
as too crazy.

01:23:55.890 --> 01:24:00.840
And now, that is part of the
broad-based platform that's

01:24:00.840 --> 01:24:04.140
accepted that minimum wage
won't destroy economy,

01:24:04.140 --> 01:24:06.360
but will help people
who work, as part

01:24:06.360 --> 01:24:10.500
of this near-full employment,
to be able to support themselves

01:24:10.500 --> 01:24:12.300
and their families.

01:24:12.300 --> 01:24:14.430
I think that that's
one of the big things.

01:24:14.430 --> 01:24:17.850
We have a candidate I just read
about, last name Yang, who's

01:24:17.850 --> 01:24:21.270
running his presidential
primary campaign

01:24:21.270 --> 01:24:24.210
on universal basic income.

01:24:24.210 --> 01:24:28.690
We have a mayor, Michael Tubbs,
in Stockton, California, who

01:24:28.690 --> 01:24:32.100
is doing an experimental
pilot project

01:24:32.100 --> 01:24:35.160
on universal basic
income to see if that

01:24:35.160 --> 01:24:36.780
could be part of the solution.

01:24:36.780 --> 01:24:38.880
He's getting big
backing from tech.

01:24:38.880 --> 01:24:42.960
So I just want to say that we're
going to see all kinds of ideas

01:24:42.960 --> 01:24:46.232
to deal with the economic
problems that we have.

01:24:46.232 --> 01:24:47.940
We're going to see
those manifest in some

01:24:47.940 --> 01:24:49.800
of the campaigns coming up.

01:24:49.800 --> 01:24:53.670
We'll know everybody that's
in the field in eight weeks.

01:24:53.670 --> 01:24:56.460
Everyone who's
running for president.

01:24:56.460 --> 01:24:58.410
Because we look
back, Barack Obama

01:24:58.410 --> 01:25:01.860
announced January 18 before--

01:25:01.860 --> 01:25:03.150
it's coming up.

01:25:03.150 --> 01:25:06.325
And I think the economic
solution, particularly

01:25:06.325 --> 01:25:07.700
around the working
poor, is going

01:25:07.700 --> 01:25:10.110
to be one of the
central issues that

01:25:10.110 --> 01:25:13.050
the presidential candidates
on the Democratic side

01:25:13.050 --> 01:25:14.810
are going to have to address.

01:25:14.810 --> 01:25:18.877
- We have gone over by a
few minutes, so I am-- well,

01:25:18.877 --> 01:25:19.960
I guess-- what do we have?

